<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="14.[136,1452,158,869]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,503,662,688]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Distribution and habitat:</emphasis>
―Only one collection has been made; it is most probably a local endemic. In periodically, inundated forest patches.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="14.[136,1452,158,869]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,436,734,760]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Conservation status:</emphasis>
―Critically Endangered. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barfod &amp; Heatubun" authorityYear="2022" box="[725,932,734,760]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Licuala" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="suprafolia">
<emphasis box="[725,932,734,760]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Licuala suprafolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from only one site that is threatened by a logging concession and palm oil plantations. It has not been recorded subsequently.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[136,1452,158,869]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,328,806,832]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Etymology:</emphasis>
―The epithet refers to the inflorescences that are exposed above the crown at flowering, an unusual feature in the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
